<h2 class="title">Datavis with ggplot2</h2>


<p>The <a href="http://docs.ggplot2.org/current/">ggplot2</a> package is a plotting system for R, based on the grammar of graphics, which tries to take the good parts of base and lattice graphics and none of the bad parts.</p>

<div id="introduction-plotting-with-ggplot2" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="I"></a> 1. Introduction: Plotting with ggplot2</h4>
<p>First, install and load the ggplot2 package</p>
<pre class="r"><code>install.packages(&quot;ggplot2&quot;)
library(ggplot2)</code></pre>
<p>For this session, we will explore the <code>iris</code> data that is already pre-loaded in R.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>head(iris)</code></pre>

<p>You can read about the data by typing</p>
<pre class="r"><code>?iris</code></pre>
<p><br /></p>
<p><a name="a1"></a><strong>1.1. A simple function: qplot </strong></p>
<p>The general formula is <code>qplot(x, y, ...)</code>. To produce a basic scatter plot, type</p>
<pre class="r"><code>qplot(x=Sepal.Length, y=Petal.Length, data=iris)   </code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>Adding color per species and size depending of petals width</p>
<pre class="r"><code>qplot(Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, data=iris,
      color=Species, size=Petal.Width, 
      xlab=&quot;Sepal&quot;, ylab=&quot;Petal&quot;, main=&quot;Iris dataset&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>We also add a title and labels for the x and y-axis, using <code>main</code>, <code>xlab</code>and <code>ylab</code>.</p>
<p>To start at 0 for the y-axis: add <code>qplot(...,ylim=c(0,35))</code><br />
This set lower and upper bounds for y axis.<br />
You can do the same for the x-axis</p>
<pre class="r"><code>qplot(Sepal.Length, Petal.Length, data=iris, 
      color=Species, size=Petal.Width, alpha=I(0.7), 
      xlab=&quot;Sepal Length&quot;, ylab=&quot;Petal Length&quot;, main=&quot;Iris dataset&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> By setting the alpha of each point to 0.7, we reduce the effects of overplotting.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<p><a name="a2"></a> <strong>1.2. A robust function: ggplot</strong></p>
<p>General formula:<br />
<code>ggplot(data, aes(x,y)) + geom_*()</code><br />
ggplot begins a plot that you finish by adding layers to, using <code>geom()</code>. ggplot provides more control than qplot().</p>
<ul>
<li><em>aes</em>: aesthetic, visual properties of the graph
<ul>
<li><em>options aes</em>: color, fill, shape, size</li>
</ul></li>
<li><em>geom</em>: graphical property
<ul>
<li>geom_line; geom_bar; geom_histogram</li>
<li>geom_chart; geom_hex, geom_c(point,line) etc. You can specify for each geom the aesthetic mappings, and a default stat and position adjustment: <code>geom_*(aes(color=, fill=, size=....))</code></li>
</ul></li>
<li><em>additional elements</em> :
<ul>
<li>You can add a smoothing trend : + <code>geom_smooth (method=&quot;lm&quot;)</code></li>
<li>You can change the background (Themes): <code>+ theme_bw()</code>, `+theme_classic()</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(mtcars,aes(x=disp,y=mpg))+ geom_point()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> From now on, we will only work using ggplot.</p>
<p><a href="#">Back to top</a></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="scatterplot" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="1"></a> 2. Scatterplot</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price, color=clarity)) + geom_point()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> Adding color: the color of the points is determined by the clarity of the diamonds.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price, color=cut)) + geom_point()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> Here we changed the color by the parameter “cut” of the dataset diamonds.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price, color=clarity, size=cut)) + geom_point()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> Here we changed the size of the points according to the parameter cut.</p>
<p><a href="#">Back to top</a></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="faceting" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="2"></a> 3. Faceting</h4>
<ul>
<li>Divide your plot up into multiple plots, one for each level.<br />
</li>
<li><code>facet_*()</code> function</li>
</ul>
<p><a name="2.a"></a> <strong>3.1. Facet wrap</strong></p>
<p>Write a tilde (~), and then the attribute we would like to divide the plots by (here “clarity”)</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price, color=cut)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~ clarity)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p><a name="2.b"></a> <strong>3.2. Facet grid</strong></p>
<p>To divide your graph based on <strong>two different attributes</strong>: <code>facet_grid()</code><br />
Here we could use <code>&quot;color ~ clarity&quot;</code>. The tilde (~) means “explained by.”</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price, color=cut)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(color ~ clarity)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p><a href="#">Back to top</a></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="title-and-axis" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="3"></a> 4. Title and axis</h4>
<p>Title: add to the end of the line of code <code>ggtile()</code></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(carat,price)) + geom_point() + ggtitle(&quot;My scatter plot&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>Axis label: <code>xlab</code> and <code>ylab</code></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point() + ggtitle(&quot;My scatter plot&quot;) + xlab(&quot;Weight (carats)&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>To limit the range of the x or the y axes: <code>xlim</code> or <code>ylim</code></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point() + ggtitle(&quot;My scatter plot&quot;) + xlab(&quot;Weight (carats)&quot;) + xlim(0, 2)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> This code limits the diamonds weight from 0 to 2 carats.</p>
<p>Another possibility is to put one of the axes on a log scale. You can do this with the <code>scale_y_log10()</code> function:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point() + ggtitle(&quot;My scatter plot&quot;) + xlab(&quot;Weight (carats)&quot;) + scale_y_log10()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p><a href="#">Back to top</a></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="histograms" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="4"></a> 5. Histograms</h4>
<p>Using the data set diamonds, we visualize the density of the distribution of price:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=price)) + geom_histogram()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> You notice that we do not precise the y axis in the aesthetic. Indeed, using histograms to visualize the density of distribution, y is directly equal to the density within each bin!</p>
<p>You can change the width of each bin as an option, using <code>binwidth</code> inside the <code>geom_histogram()</code> function:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=price)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=2000)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>And we can add all the options that we used with a basci scatter plot. For instance, the <code>facet_wrap()</code> function:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=price)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=200) + facet_wrap(~ clarity)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>Here, all the subplots share the same y-axis: this makes it hard to interpret the frequencies…<br />
Some subplots have far more points than others.</p>
<p>To have different y-axis for each subplot, add <code>scale=&quot;free_y&quot;</code></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=price)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=200) + facet_wrap(~ clarity, scale=&quot;free_y&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> The same function can be used differentiating for the x-axis.</p>
<p>To make a <strong>stacked histogram</strong> based here on the clarity attribute: Try adding the <code>fill</code> aesthetic within the aesthetic of the <code>ggplot()</code> function.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=price, fill=clarity)) + geom_histogram()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p><a href="#">Back to top</a></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="boxplots-and-violin-plots" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="5"></a> 6. Boxplots and violin plots</h4>
<p>Boxplots are useful to compare multiple distributions. Compare the distribution of the price within each color using <code>geom_boxplot()</code>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=color, y=price)) + geom_boxplot()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>Put the y-axis on a log scale: we get a better sense of how the distribution of price differs across multiple colors.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=color, y=price)) + geom_boxplot() + scale_y_log10()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<p>A box plot will always look like a square. We can instead view the distribution as a density using a “violin plot”.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=color, y=price)) + geom_violin() + scale_y_log10()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=color, y=price)) + geom_violin() + scale_y_log10() + facet_wrap(~ clarity)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," title alt width="480" style="display: block; margin: auto;" /> We used the <code>facet_wrap()</code> function to display multiple subplots.</p>
<p><a href="#">Back to top</a></p>
<hr />
</div>
<div id="output-and-saving" class="section level4">
<h4><a name="6"></a> 7. Output and saving</h4>
<p>Run your line of code and save it to a variable. For instance, call it p for plot:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>p = ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point()</code></pre>
<p>Save that plot to a file</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggsave(filename=&quot;diamonds.png&quot;, p)  ## as a png
ggsave(filename=&quot;diamonds.pdf&quot;, p)  ## as a pdf
ggsave(filename=&quot;diamonds.jpeg&quot;, p) ## as a jpeg</code></pre>
<p>One useful shortcut is that if you just displayed a plot, like in a line like this:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point()
ggsave(&quot;diamonds.png&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>Then <code>ggsave()</code> will know to save that plot by default when you perform <code>ggsave</code> - you don’t even have to tell it which plot you’re saving.</p>
<p><a href="#">Back to top</a></p>
</div>
